When testing on IE 11.09600.17690 I found that the pagination would reset when the user clicked in the search text field. As it turns out the input event was being triggered so I have made this little patch.

```
// view -> table state
element.bind('input', function (evt) {
    evt = evt.originalEvent || evt;
    var oldValue = $(evt.target).data("oldValue"); 
    if ((oldValue === undefined || evt.target.value != oldValue) &&
        !((oldValue === undefined && evt.target.value == "") || evt.target.value == oldValue)) {
        if (promise !== null) {
            $timeout.cancel(promise);
        }
        promise = $timeout(function () {
            tableCtrl.search(evt.target.value, scope.predicate || '');
            $(evt.target).data('oldValue', evt.target.value)
            promise = null;
        }, throttle);
    }
});
```

When you have a column, lets say 'visitors', with the following rows: *2, 45, 33, 10, undefined, undefined*

It gets sorted as:
**asc:** 2, 10, 33, 45, undefined, undefined
**desc:** undefined, undefined, 45, 33, 10, 2

Which is, especially for desc, not what you want.

I've created a getter function to solve this:
````scope.getter = {
        visitors: function (value) {
            return value.visitors || 0 ;
        }
    }````

Maybe it's an idea to make this default behaviour?

